{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17471451","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17471451"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:48:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:48:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"371"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/371"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.03,0.08,0.17,0.61]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"371"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83051"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"371","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/371"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"371"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68115"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"260"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1984"},{"type":"tags","id":"2860"},{"type":"tags","id":"5810"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"455"},{"type":"contributions","id":"523"},{"type":"contributions","id":"567"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7052"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83051","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/83051"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA seven-year-old girl presents to the Emergency Department with a one-day history of left knee pain and inability to bear weight. She has no significant medical history and her immunisations are up to date. Her father has Haemophilia A. She does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears distressed. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 105/65 mmHg, respiratory rate 22/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.5\u00b0C. Her left knee is swollen, warm, and exquisitely tender to light touch. She resists any passive or active movement of the knee.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely finding on synovial fluid analysis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Prolonged prothrombin time","Rhomboid shaped crystals","Gram negative bacilli","Prolonged partial thromboplastin time","Gram positive cocci"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis child presents with classic features of septic arthritis: acute onset joint pain, fever, and severely limited range of motion. In fully immunised children, \u003Cem\u003EStaphylococcus aureus\u003C/em\u003E and \u003Cem\u003EStreptococcus\u003C/em\u003E species (both of which are \u003Cstrong\u003EGram positive cocci\u003C/strong\u003E) account for the majority of septic arthritis cases. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGram negative bacilli\u003C/strong\u003E are uncommon causes of septic arthritis in immunised children. These organisms, particularly \u003Cem\u003EHaemophilus influenzae\u003C/em\u003E, are more frequently seen in non-immunised children or in specific risk groups such as intravenous drug users.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERhomboid shaped crystals\u003C/strong\u003E are characteristic of calcium pyrophosphate deposition disease (pseudogout). This condition is exceptionally rare in children and would not present with fever and systemic illness. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProlonged prothrombin time\u003C/strong\u003E reflects dysfunction of the extrinsic clotting pathway, typically seen in vitamin K deficiency or liver disease. Neither condition fits with this acute presentation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProlonged partial thromboplastin time\u003C/strong\u003E might be considered given the family history of Haemophilia A. However, this X-linked recessive condition typically only results in female children being asymptomatic carriers. Furthermore, haemarthrosis would not account for the fever and systemic features.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Gram positive cocci, particularly Staphylococcus aureus, are the most common cause of septic arthritis in fully vaccinated children.","The triad of fever, joint pain, and reduced range of motion strongly suggests septic arthritis in children.","Arthrocentesis is essential for diagnosis of septic arthritis and should not be delayed by other investigations."],"references":["RACGP - Septic arthritis in children. https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2015/april/septic-arthritis-in-children/","P\u00e4\u00e4kk\u00f6nen M. Septic arthritis in children: diagnosis and treatment. Pediatric Health Med Ther. 2017;8:65-68. Published 2017 May 18. doi:10.2147/PHMT.S115429","Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68115"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"371"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"68115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/68115"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-02-01T12:56:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-02-01T12:57:18+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"371"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"83051"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHead